<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 94 / British soldier killed in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SARAJEVO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serbs killed a British UN soldier yesterday in an attack on a UN
convoy using a commercial route into Sarajevo which the Serbs had closed to
put pressure on the United Nations and the Bosnian government in peace
negotiations. The attack came as Mr William Perry, US defence secretary,
warned of 'consequences' for the Serbs if they did not drop their opposition
to the peace plan by Saturday.
Bosnian Serbs opened fire on the convoy, wounding two British soldiers and
one civilian and blowing up a fuel tanker. One of the soldiers was shot in
the chest and died later of his wounds. UN sources said Nato warplanes were
called in but did not fire because they could not identify a target. Lt-Gen
Sir Michael Rose, UN commander in Bosnia, said Serbs had mistook the white
trucks and jeeps, bearing UN markings, for civilian vehicles but a British
officer on the convoy said the UN had been directly targeted. Last night
French forces, who went to recover British vehicles stranded in the attack,
were fired on.
</TEXT>
