<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / International Company News: IBM plans global superhighway
network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines plans to create a worldwide high-speed voice
and data network to offer advanced communications services to multinational
business users.
The initiative reflects IBM's determination to claim leadership in
network-centric computing, commonly known as information superhighway
services.
Mr Lou Gerstner, chairman, has identified network-centric computing as one
of six strategic imperatives for IBM's recovery and growth.
The company has formed a business unit, IBM Global Network, with a staff of
5,000 people, to develop and operate the network. It will be headed by Mr
John Whiteside, formerly of MCI Communications, the US long-distance
telephone service company.
'The IBM Global Network will be the business persons Internet,' said Mr
Whiteside, referring to the global web of computer networks that link tens
of thousands of computers. Like Internet, IBM's Global Network will enable
companies to share multimedia data and services among their computers
worldwide.
'The computing environment of the future is one where networks do much more
than just provide for the transport of information,' said Mr James
Cannavino, IBM senior-vice president for strategy and development.
'Applications and services will be embedded in high-speed voice and data
networks, and people who use these services - whether to fill out an order
entry form or to watch a movie - do so by accessing the network, rather than
a software application sitting on their desktop,' he predicted. 'The IBM
Global Network will accelerate the evolution to this new computing model.'
To create its global network IBM will draw together existing national and
regional networks including Advantis, a US joint venture between IBM and
Sears Roebuck and IBM information networks throughout the world.
The network will cover more than 700 cities around the globe, providing
networking-based services to 23,000 companies in 94 countries.
IBM Global Network will work in partnership with IBM's outsourcing
businesses to offer a broad range of information processing services.
</TEXT>
