<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / International Company News: Freeport impresses with a net
income of Dollars 4.63m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Higher metals and phosphate fertiliser prices helped Freeport-McMoRan, the
New Orleans-based natural resources group, report second-quarter net income
of Dollars 4.63m, or 3 cents a share, compared with a net loss of Dollars
77.4m, or 54 cents, a year ago.
For the six months to June 30, Freeport recorded net income of Dollars 17m,
or 12 cents, against a net loss of Dollars 132.7m, or 93 cents.
Second-quarter revenues benefited from increased sales volumes too:
Freeport's metals affiliate, Freeport-McMoRan Copper &amp; Gold, sold 168.6m lbs
of copper and 185,400 troy ounces of gold, up from 140m lbs and 127,200
ounces in the same quarter of 1993.
A price protection hedging programme also lifted the average realised price
of copper to Dollars 1.02 a lb against 90 cents while gold sale prices
averaged Dollars 353.82 an ounce compared with Dollars 338.60.
However, copper production costs were abnormally high in the quarter - at
61.4 cents a lb against 59.4 cents in the first quarter - because of low ore
grades and recoveries. Freeport said costs would be significantly lower in
the second half of 1994.
</TEXT>
