<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Israel has no interest in seeking Lebanese soil
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Israel said yesterday it did not seek 'one square inch' of Lebanese
territory or 'one cubic metre' of Lebanese water and would sign a peace
treaty and withdraw Israeli forces from southern Lebanon as soon as the
Beirut government demonstrated it controlled its sovereign soil.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, said Israel would respect the
accepted international border in any peace deal but complained Syrian troops
and Iranian revolutionary guards were still in Lebanon and that an 'all out
war' existed between Israeli and Israeli-backed Arab forces and the
guerrillas of the Hizbollah or Party of God were being supplied by Iran
through Syria.
Mr Rabin accused Syria of failing to use its 'preventive capability' to rein
in Hizbollah attacks. Once the Lebanese goverment proved it was in full
control of its territory and could guarantee the security of its border
Israel would agree to peace.
'I believe they are capable if somebody from the outside will not
interfere,' he said.
</TEXT>
