<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Fiat executives cleared
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lawyers for Fiat have won an important battle to clear the group's senior
executives of involvement in a corruption scandal concerning payment of some
L100bn (Pounds 41m) in bribes to politicians to secure contracts for the
Rome metro. A Rome judge late on Monday dismissed the case against Mr Cesare
Romiti, Fiat's chief executive officer, and Mr Francesco Mattioli, the motor
group's chief financial officer. The case against Mr Carlo De Benedetti,
head of Olivetti, was dismissed earlier. However, the same judge sent for
trial a group of prominent ex-politicians and businessmen including: Mr
Bettino Craxi, former Socialist leader; Mr Vittorio Sbardella, the Rome
Christian Democrat close to former premier Giulio Andreotti; and Mr Franco
Nobili, former head of the Iri state holding company. So far L6bn of bribes
has been recovered from Swiss bank accounts. This money has been returned to
the municipality of Rome, which had launched a civil suit in the
proceedings.
</TEXT>
