<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of Tunisia (8): Palms and prosperity - The date
export market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Since time immemorial, the date palm has been the source of wealth and the
symbol of prosperity in certain Mediterranean and Middle Eastern countries.
As is true with the olive oil it produces, Tunisia belongs to a small group
of countries which accounts for virtually all the dates produced in the
world.
Though it ranks second to Iraq as a producer and recently as an exporter,
Tunisia can claim that its deglet nour date (the fingers of light) is the
finest palm date in the world. The value of exports has more than doubled to
USDollars 55m over the past 10 years. North Africa's smallest country
possesses an undeniable comparative advantage where dates are concerned but
the challenge presented by higher quality control, better packaging and
modern marketing techniques is one which confronts many sectors in the food
processing industries. Unlike other produce, however, European Union quotas
do not pose a problem.
Production of dates in Tunisia has always rested in private hands - 20,000
hectares, spread among thousands of small holders in the oasis around the
towns of Tozeur and Kebili which lie on the northern and southern slopes of
the Shott El Jerid salt flatlands of southern Tunisia. Three million date
palm trees also produce wood and palm leaves widely used for building,
fencing and fuel. As old palms stop producing dates, new ones have been
planted and annual production figures today stand at 100,000 tonnes of dates
every year.
Date palms have to be individually pollinated and the fruit hand-picked,
skills which risk becoming sparse as young Tunisians from the oasis are
increasingly tempted by easier jobs offered in local hotels or in towns
along the coast. Many oases are half abandoned today, yet their well-being
is essential not only to keep the population on the land but to attract
foreign tourists, who are discovering the pleasures of travelling in the
desert in winter time in ever greater numbers.
In the mid-1980s, the rising price of dates on world markets resulted in
fast-growing incomes in the oasis. But higher incomes were not matched by
greater efforts to ensure quality (which in particular means avoiding
worms), by improving irrigation and fertilising methods. As world prices
fell in the late 1980s because of greater competition, Tunisian producers
learnt the hard way that there is no such thing as a free ride. According to
exporters in Tunis, they now have a greater appreciation of the absolute
need to improve quality.
Until Mr Habib Bourguiba, the former president, halted his experiment in
collectivised farming in 1969, the Societe Tunisienne des Industries
Laitieres held a monopoly in respect of the conditioning and exporting of
dates. The conditioning monopoly was abolished in 1971 and the export
monopoly ended soon afterwards. Many of those involved in conditioning are
actively promoting sales in the European Union where virtually all Tunisian
dates are sold.
Packaging has been much improved in recent years to meet European countries'
requirements and break the stranglehold of a few middlemen in Marseilles who
were, as one Tunisian exporter put it, 'a necessary evil.'
Transport costs, however, remain high. Some dates are shipped in lorries.
There is a container service between Tunis and Antwerp, even between Tunis
and Los Angeles, but not between Tunis and Marseilles. Dates delivered to
Los Angeles are thus only one-third more expensive than those delivered to
France. Bringing down transport costs is no easy matter but Tunisian
exporters are trying to meet the challenge.
Worldwide production of dates amounts to about 1.5m tonnes annually,
one-third of which is traded internationally. Tunisia is the second largest
exporter, with 20,000 tonnes a year. Until the beginning of this decade, the
most important exporter was Iraq, whose 200,000 tonnes of exports of
lesser-quality dates were traditionally shipped in bulk, mostly to Asian
markets, especially India. In recent years both production and exports of
Iraqi dates have plummeted, their place being taken by dates from Iran and
Pakistan which between them export roughly 150,000 tonnes every year to
Asian markets.
Tunisia has increased its exports since 1984 by nearly 50 per cent. Unlike
Iraq, its dates are sold in small, attractive package boxes and they all go
to European markets - 8,000 tonnes to France, 4,000 to Italy, 2,000 to Spain
and Belgium respectively, 1,500 to the UK and 1,000 to Germany. The dates
are increasingly sent directly to different European markets and distributed
through big importers of dried fruit and foodstuffs, such as Geest of the UK
and Torres of Spain.
Tunisia faces competition from two sources today: Algeria and, increasingly,
Israel. Algeria exports 8,000 tonnes of dates a year and has over the past
two or three years undercut Tunisian prices as its producers are desperate
to earn foreign exchange. Such competition is viewed by some Tunisians as
disloyal. Others point out that by forcing them to cut transport costs and
improve packaging and presentation, their neighbours are in the long run
doing them a service.
Israel exports 2,000 tonnes of deglet nour every year and has the advantage
over Tunisia that its dates ripen three weeks earlier and are sold in Europe
at the beginning of October in the run-up to the Christmas period. The onus
is therefore on the Tunisian producers to find ways in which they can
improve their methods of stocking and production or get dates to mature
earlier. However, Israeli dates have a disadvantage in that their skins are
thicker than those of Tunisian dates. But to convince European buyers of the
quality difference, Tunisian marketing and promotion efforts will have to be
stepped up.
The other important exporter is California, which sells 5,000 tonnes of
dates abroad a year. Californian dates are of poorer quality than those from
Tunisia but, needless to say, marketing techniques are far more
sophisticated.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TNZ  Tunisia, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0179 Fruits and Tree Nuts, NEC.
    P5148 Fresh Fruits and Vegetables.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Production.
    MKTS  Market shares.
    MKTS  Foreign trade.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
