London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT943-11960</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EG1ANAF3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940727
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of Tunisia (7): Hard life on the land - Francis
Ghiles looks at a quiet revolution in farming
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The past 12 months have been difficult for Tunisian farmers. After four good
years of rainfall, which produced an average cereal crop of 1.6m tonnes
annually, output of wheat and barley in 1994 is expected to fall to half
that figure. This, in turn, will shave 1 to 1.5 per cent off the rate of
growth of gross domestic product and will more than double the cost of
imports to around Dollars 250m to Dollars 300m.
In the past, a year of drought often led to disaster, but this is no longer
the case today. The country's economy is far more diversified and 1994 shows
signs of being an excellent year for tourism. In farming, the growing spread
of irrigation and wider use of fertilisers are leading to more diversified
and better quality crops.
Despite the progress of recent years, the sector still contributes on
average 15 per cent of GDP while employing 45 per cent of the labour force.
To enact reforms in a country characterised by semi-arid climate and a very
fragmented pattern of ownership, where 80 per cent of farms comprise 20
hectares or less, is no easy task.
But, as a younger generation of well-trained technicians take up new posts
and as more of the 500,000 hectares of state-owned land is leased for 25
years to private companies - which include smallholders and foreign
companies such as Shell - a quiet revolution is afoot, whose chances of
success depend on a sustained effort over the next decade.
These changes are also encouraged by a policy aimed at developing and
conserving water resources and ensuring that even remote areas get access to
drinking water and electricity. The latter fits in with the policy of doing
more for the poorer south and western hinterlands. That has been a
characteristic of regional development since the late 1980s.
If anything, the troubles in neighbouring Algeria will reinforce the
determination of Tunisia's leaders to ensure that those who live in the
poorer parts of the country do not feel left out of the slowly rising
prosperity which characterises its coastal and richer farming provinces.
The quiet revolution in the countryside can be attributed to four broad
factors:
The state has divested itself of a good half of the land it has held since
French farms were 'nationalised' 30 years ago. The land contains some of
Tunisia's most fertile soil and is let on leases of up to 25 years, either
to Tunisians who are often agricultural engineers, or to large Tunisian and
foreign firms. The best example of the latter is the domain of M'Raissa,
which is being developed by Shell together with Tunisian banking and
insurance groups.
The result is a switch from a 'socialist' form of farming, which normally
simply ensured that a given piece of land could feed those who worked it but
little more, to a form of farming which seeks to increase production, pays
serious attention to quality and requires a more educated workforce. The
ultimate goal of such developments is the production and export of
high-quality produce, anything from blood oranges to wine, from flowers to
seedless grapes.
The second factor is the freeing of input prices and the raising of producer
prices. Since 1986, when reforms aimed at liberalising the running of the
country's economy were introduced, the price of inputs, notably fertilisers,
has increased by nearly three-quarters and that of water by roughly 10 per
cent a year. The need to utilise resources more rationally is now widely
understood.
Complaints abound, however, about the bureaucratic ways of many of the 4,000
civil servants who sit in the sprawling Ministry of Agriculture in Tunis.
Many Tunisians interested in farming consider that a re-organisation of the
ministry is long overdue.
A third factor is related to the efforts under way to distribute Tunisian
products more widely in the European Union. Valiant efforts are being made
by the private sector to package olive oil, dates and other fruit more
attractively and to ensure steady high quality, both vital necessities when
faced with international competition. Ways are being sought to lower
transport costs, which are often high, to think of how best to create a
'Tunisia' label for certain products, to diversify from traditional markets,
such as France. All these moves are forcing painful changes further up the
prod- uction line.
The production of wine provides a good example of change. In 1963, Tunisia
produced 1.4m hectolitres of wine, 90 per cent of which was exported to
reinforce French wines. By 1978 production had fallen to 300,000 hectolitres
and the vines had grown old. More than one-third of the vines had been
pulled up and no wine was exported. There was no incentive to improve
quality as local drinkers or foreigners on package tours had no palate for
fine wines.
By the early 1980s, replanting started; a few years later new varieties were
introduced, such as Cabernet Franc and Merlot. Production started to
increase and now stands at around 450,000 hectolitres a year. New markets in
Europe, most notably in Germany which accounts for 60 per cent of the value
of wine exports, were being developed.
The Office du Vin is also making efforts to modernise the methods of making
wine and a new generation of bottles and labels is soon to hit the market.
The value of exports remains a modest Dollars 9m annually but the industry
accounts for 1.5m days of work every year.
A fourth factor is of a more social nature: to try to make life on the land
less harsh. This is vital to avoid a greater drift of population into
already large cities, virtually all of which are situated on the coast.
Also, there is the wider issue of preserving the environment, which the
Tunisian authorities have taken to heart in recent years. The social
stability of Tunisia commands that the income of the poorer north-west and
central southern regions be improved and that those living in poorer areas
do not feel left out of the coastal prosperity.
Many jobs, notably in the bloated civil service and tourist industry pay
relatively high incomes for work which is infinitely easier than tilling the
land. The minimal daily farm wage is only TD6, though many skilled
farmworkers earn far more, especially in the richer areas. Only 18 per cent
of those who work on the land - and this includes an ever-growing number of
women - are covered by the social security net, in sharp contrast to those
who work in industry and the civil service.
The challenge that the auth- orities face is one of improving the lot of
those who live on the land and tying higher wages, wherever possible, to
increases in productivity. To attract younger people (the average age of
those who till the land is 55), they must offer induce- ments even before
the results would justify them on strictly economic grounds.
The fight to improve production, to enhance the quality of what is grown and
gain export markets will, however, remain hampered by the ever-growing
fragment- ation of property and the considerable confusion that surrounds
title deeds. Such problems, however, are not susceptible of easy solution.
</TEXT>
