<DATE>940727
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of Tunisia (6): No room for religious parties -
President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali provides answers on the key issues facing
the country in an interview with Roger Matthews
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On the threat posed to Tunisia if Islamic fundamentalists come to power in
Algeria.
Of course, it could pose some difficulties for us. But it would not be a
real threat. In some ways, it is like a sickness. If you are healthy and
strong, then you will not be infected. We have a healthy body, so we have no
reason to fear anything.
On the causes of fundamentalism.
First, it is important to make clear that to some extent fundamentalism was
of our own making, and was at one time encouraged in order to combat the
threat of communism. Such groups were fostered in the universities and
elsewhere at that time in order to offset the communists and to strike a
balance. This is not really going back to the roots of the issue, but is one
aspect of it.
This phenomenon has also spread in some regions, not primarily because of
religious reasons, but because of social and economic causes, especially
where there have been pockets of poverty. Basically it is a socio-economic
problem.
How Tunisia has approached the problem.
Our approach has been multi-dimensional and we have avoided making only a
security response, although of course we have applied the law. We have
adopted policies which tackle the economic and social problems, by taking
care of the poorer regions and helping the poorest section of society. We
have tried to go to the roots of the problem.
My background in the military and security has provided me with a rich
experience in understanding the problem. For example, when in the past there
were demonstrations on the streets it was noticeable that the protesters
attacked the outward symbols of wealth. They threw stones at Mercedes
limousines and at luxury villas and houses. They showed their resentment at
the rich.
This was evidence that the real origin of the protests was social. It would
take hours to explain the full reasons for the phenomenon. I have been aware
of it since the 1970s and I was the first to write a paper on the subject of
fundamentalists and the danger they posed to the government here.
The role of democracy
In Algeria, the government sought to introduce a ready-made model of
democracy. But what is really important is what the people understand by
democracy. For example, in November 1987, two days after I had become
president, the minister of the interior told me that people who said they
were homeless had tried to invade some newly-constructed buildings.
They said that they had the right to invade them because under a democracy
everyone had a right to a house. That was their understanding of democracy.
It shows that the development of democracy is very much a matter of
education and of progressing step by step.
This approach does not mean there is no freedom or justice. Doing it by
stages means first introducing it at the level of the schools and to avoid
making wrong steps. In this we are being successful. Democracy is a matter
of mentality and a way of life. People have to be taught.
Democracy is an overall concept. It is not just politics but also health
care, housing and the right to a job. There cannot be democracy without
development, and there cannot be development without democracy. But freedom
of expression alone does not necessarily bring jobs and drinking water for
the people.
If people are not mentally prepared for democracy it could be a catastrophe.
The examples elsewhere in the world are obvious. The fundamentalists are
basically the enemies of democracy. They struggle to take people back to the
Middle Ages and the days of the Islamic caliphate. Where is the democracy in
that?
According to the laws and constitution of Tunisia, there is no room for
religious parties. They will never happen here. We shall never embark on
this course. It would be a catastrophe for this country and its people if we
were ever to give permission for the formation of a religious party.
As long as I am here, as president or not, I will continue to combat the
creation of a religious party. That is my conviction.
Tunisia's links with Europe, the Arab world and north Africa
Tunisia's natural environment is constituted first by the Maghreb, then by
the Arab world. To deny this would be to deny our very identity. But it is
also true that Tunisia has always been linked economically with Europe,
which is our major supplier of equipment and technology and our favoured
partner in the commercial domain.
What is more, Tunisia is one of the favourite destinations of European
tourists. But these days there is also less room for co-operation among
single countries alone. Instead they are very much coming to be seen as part
of larger groupings. So we are trying to co-operate with the Maghreb Union,
which adds extra weight to our co-operation with the EU.
On establishing full diplomatic relations with Israel
Tunisia has unfailingly provided our Palestinian brothers and sisters with
active support for the re-establishment of their legitimate national rights.
Our relief and optimism at the signing of agreements between the PLO and
Israel were felt all the more strongly because of the considerable
contribution we made. It appears that the Palestinian problem is on the path
to a lasting political solution. But we cannot say the problem has been
truly solved until the Palestinians have recovered all their legitimate
rights. We will avoid making any hasty decisions that might compromise their
interests, and at the same time we will continue to provide our full support
for the peace process.
On the future of Tunisia
Previously an underdeveloped country, we have been successful in getting to
the intermediate stage and it is my ambition that we should be a member of
the family of democratic nations. That is a political decision. I have been
urging Tunisians to work harder. Now I am urging them to work better in
order to catch up with the developed countries, to be competitive with them,
especially in the event of there being a free trade zone with the European
Union. We have to enhance the quality of our goods. Whoever consumes what he
does not produce is not truly independent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TNZ  Tunisia, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
