<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of The Bank of England (7): The driving force behind
shake-up / Profile of Rupert Pennant-Rea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rupert Pennant-Rea's recruitment as deputy-governor in 1993, from the
editorship of the Economist, caused considerable surprise. True, he had
worked at the Bank in the mid-1970s, but before that he had worked as an
official at the General and Municipal Workers' Union.
The Bank has traditionally liked to have an outsider in one of its two top
posts, and with Eddie George being promoted from within, the deputy-governor
needed to be an external candidate. But rather than the conventional choice
of a clearing banker, Norman Lamont opted for Pennant-Rea, a journalist.
Former deputy-governor Sir Kit McMahon described the choice as 'a
breathtaking insult to the Bank'.
However, there was a certain logic to the move. The Economist, where
Pennant-Rea became editor from 1986, regards itself as a cut above most
newspapers, rather as the Bank looks down loftily on the clearers.
Pennant-Rea personified the 'journalist as detached thinker' approach in
which the Economist specialises; he was expected therefore to add some
vigour to the policy debates at the Bank.
In fact, much of his first year has been taken up with the old fashioned
deputy-governor's task of managing the Bank. He was the driving force behind
the Bank's reorganisation, which involved him in hard decisions, both at the
macro level (the demise of the old international division) and at the micro
level (the departure of a number of senior staff).
His journalistic skills have shown up in a change of tone. Central bankers'
public utterances are renowned for conveying as little information as
possible in a generally turgid style. Pennant-Rea's speeches (which he
writes himself) even essay the odd joke - for example, 'monetary restraint
is not a hair-shirt but it has to be a habit' - and a daring note of
candour: 'At the Bank of England, we are merely part of the supply lines. As
such, we have the ability to mess things up - and our record shows we have
often used it.'
Former colleagues say his style is little changed by his move to the Bank -
his pullovers still flout the normal conventions of City attire. 'He is one
of life's immutable people,' according to one, while those who know him now
say 'he still has a slightly undergraduate air'. His informality means that
Bank staff address him as 'Rupert' rather than the traditional 'Mr Deputy'.
But some of his opinions have changed. The Economist took the line that the
Bank should not be involved in banking supervision, but Pennant-Rea
confessed to the Treasury and Civil Service select committee that he had
been converted to the Bank view.
Friends say he is enjoying the job tremendously and is getting on well with
Eddie George. He himself has hinted that he expects to be in the job for
only five years or so, and in one interview, indicated that his previous
career was not ideal training for the present job. 'My temperament is
conditioned by the last 16 years as a journalist, which is a world of quick
decisions and strong words,' he said. 'A central banker needs to be more
silent and unrevealing. I am not very good at that.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
