<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of The Bank of England (4): Accountability is core
issue - Philip Coggan examines the debate about possible independence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British economic policy debates are rarely short of what Americans call the
'high concept' solution - an idea that can be explained in a sentence.
In the past, the panaceas have varied from incomes policies through monetary
targets to membership of the exchange rate mechanism. The current 'high
concept' is Bank of England independence.
Only with an independent Bank, enthusiasts argue, can monetary policy be
freed from the interfering and inflationary hands of politicians. Only with
an independent Bank can monetary policy have the credibility to convince
sceptical international financial markets.
Enthusiasts point to the long-running, anti-inflationary success of the
Bundesbank and, more recently, to the record of New Zealand, where the
central bank has been given a precise 0-2 per cent inflation target.
In part, however, the tide of enthusiasm for Bank independence stems from
the shock created when the pound was forced out of the exchange rate
mechanism in September 1992. ERM membership had been the cornerstone of the
government's economic policy. A replacement strategy was needed - and
quickly.
Norman Lamont's decision was to give a greater role in policy to the Bank.
The publication of a quarterly inflation report by the Bank, accompanied by
an official inflation target of 1-4 per cent, was the centrepiece of the new
strategy. Kenneth Clarke, Lamont's successor, has steadily increased the
Bank's autonomy. The Bank now has the power to set the timing, if not the
direction or size, of interest rate changes. The minutes of the monthly
monetary meetings between the governor and the chancellor are now published,
six weeks after the event. This should, so the theory goes, make it clear
when the chancellor is ignoring the governor's advice and pursuing for his
own political motives a monetary policy which was too lax.
But while the government has allowed this steady trend towards de facto
independence, it has shown only modest enthusiasm for making that
independence de jure.
The issue of accountability is at the core of the debate. Bank independence
involves the ceding of control over important areas of economic policy to
unelected bankers, whose sympathies are more likely to be in tune with bond
investors than, say, the long-term unemployed.
After Norman Lamont's resignation speech, in which the former chancellor
called for Bank independence, John Major said that 'were a way to be found
to get the benefits of an independent central Bank without the loss of
parliamentary accountability, my views would be very close to that of my Rt
Hon Friend'.
The Treasury view has been that considerable steps have already been taken
to give the Bank autonomy and these need to be 'bedded down' and assessed,
before any further moves towards independence are contemplated.
Nevertheless, there is a fair head of steam behind the independence idea. As
well as Norman Lamont, another former chancellor, Lord Lawson, has come out
in support thereof. City support was shown by a Centre for Economic Policy
Research paper in 1993, which proposed that the Bank should have full
control of short-term interest rates, subject to emergency powers which the
government (with parliamentary approval) could invoke.
Both Eddie George, the governor, and the deputy-governor, Rupert
Pennant-Rea, have backed the idea, albeit with the proviso that independence
would be useless without a general anti-inflationary consensus. Quoted in
the spring issue of Central Banking, Mr Pennant-Rea said: 'What we are
really after is a greater appreciation of the benefits of a stable
macroeconomic background and anything that contributes to that better
understanding is a good thing. Frankly, until we have that understanding
spread across quite a wide range of informed opinion and parliamentary
opinion, you shouldn't be talking about independence as an imminent
possibility.'
The tercentenary has created the opportunity for some subtle lobbying in
favour of independence. One of the papers in the Bank's tercentenary
symposium, from Stanley Fischer, the soon-to-be deputy-managing director of
the International Monetary Fund, made a strong pro-independence case.
'The evidence leaves little doubt that, on average, economic performance is
better in countries with more independent central banks,' argued Mr Fischer,
concluding that 'on her 300th birthday, it is time for the Old Lady to be
allowed to take on the responsibilities of independence.'
Mr Fischer's paper sets out the intellectual case for Bank independence.
First, he argues there has been an inflationary bias in the economic policy
of most countries. One reason is seignorage, the revenue which flows to
governments from the creation of money.
A second cause may be dynamic inconsistency, the tendency for governments to
promise one thing (such as low inflation) and deliver another. Years of
experience have persuaded the public not to believe government
pronouncements on fighting inflation, and to act accordingly. Inflationary
expectations are thus built into wages and prices, making it all the more
difficult for inflation to be reduced.
Whatever the academic merits of the issue, independence for the Bank is
clearly a political matter. The chances must be that it will take another
failure of economic policy - for example, a long period in which inflation
exceeds the present 1-4 per cent target - before there is a real chance of
the Bank getting its wish.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
