<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of The Bank of England (3): Wings spread for
stability - Peter Norman analyses the recent management restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At the beginning of this month the Bank of England underwent its biggest
management restructuring since 1980.
Most of its activities, which previously were scattered through numerous
separate divisions, have been concentrated in two 'wings', one responsible
for achieving monetary stability, the other charged with securing financial
stability.
The changes, which took effect 12 months after Mr Eddie George became
governor, with Mr Rupert Pennant-Rea as his deputy, reflect the
preoccupations of both men. They want to secure lasting low inflation, a
solid financial system and efficient and competitive financial markets in
Britain.
The restructuring is intended to create a leaner, more focused bank. One
important aspect has been to bring the Bank's operational and analytical
work closer together to make it better able to respond to rapid changes and
incipient dangers in the world economy and financial markets.
Mr Pennant-Rea, brought into the Bank from the Economist newspaper in 1993,
was responsible for planning the changes. The exercise began last December
during a weekend brainstorming session of top Bank managers at Ashridge
management college in Hertfordshire. In the following months, details were
thrashed out in three working groups which reported to the deputy governor.
The immediate challenge for Mr George and Mr Pennant-Rea is to secure
support for the changes inside the Bank. As the July deadline approached it
became increasingly clear that the reorganisation had created unhappiness,
even among senior officials who recognised that the Old Lady was ready for a
shake-up.
Bank staff were prey to considerable uncertainty during the planning of the
reorganisation. Although there have been no compulsory redundancies, the
restructuring has resulted in the departure of nine of the Bank's 45 most
senior officials. It is expected to prompt the departure of another 10 to 15
of the 150 high level managers just below head of division level. Further
down the institution, the reorganisation will cost about 80 jobs among the
Bank's clerical staff.
The changes are causing one departure at the level just below deputy
governor: Mr Hugh Harris, an associate director, is to take early
retirement. However, the Bank's four executive directors have prospered
under the changes and continue in office. Two have been assigned to each of
the wings.
The monetary stability wing is headed by Mr Mervyn King, the Bank's chief
economist, and Mr Ian Plenderleith, its markets guru. Its responsibilities
extend from economic and monetary analysis of the UK and other countries,
through preparation of the bank's monetary policy advice to the government
and its quarterly inflation report, to the implementation of monetary policy
in the financial markets.
The financial stability wing comes under Mr Brian Quinn, the Bank's long
serving head of supervisory activities, and Mr Pen Kent, the man responsible
for the UK's financial infrastructure. This wing brings together all the
Bank's supervision work, including the surveillance of markets and foreign
financial systems, its work on payment, settlement and clearing systems and
liaison with other regulators in the UK and overseas.
The financial stability wing also reflects the Bank's interest in the
efficiency and competitiveness of the UK financial system, including Crest,
the Bank's project for stock exchange settlements.
There is a central services area in addition to the wings. This covers the
Bank's own finances, personnel, the information division and the centre for
banking studies, the Bank's university for teaching central banking.
The changes have resulted in the creation of a new rank of deputy director,
below executive director. The five deputy directors - Mr Graham Kentfield,
Mr John Townend, Mr Bill Allen, Mr Michael Foot and Mr Alastair Clark - look
as if they will be the next generation of top managers at the Bank.
The most striking institutional change has been the disbandment of the
Bank's international division and the integration of its work into the two
main wings. A look at the Bank's new organogram also reveals that there is
no longer an economics division, although several departments deal with
economic issues.
For those responsible for the restructuring, these changes symbolise the
point of the whole exercise.
On the economic side, for example, the Bank has given up large scale
macro-economic modelling in favour of closer study of specific issues. The
changes are intended to involve the economists more closely with the Bank's
operations in the financial markets.
The disbanding of the international division reflects a belief that it had
become a hindrance rather than a help to the Bank's main goal of achieving
monetary and financial stability. Critics argued that the division had
developed into an 'in-house foreign office' which had become detached from
the bank's main work.
Now, rather than send specialists to international meetings, Bank staff from
the governor down will be involved in international representation.
However, it is perhaps significant that no other large central bank has so
far felt the urge to follow the Bank of England's lead and scrap its
international division.
There are also concerns in Threadneedle Street that the Bank may be
sacrificing some unique skills. While the maintenance of London-based
country experts for far flung locations may seem a luxury, it has paid
dividends in the past. In 1980, for example, the US turned to the Bank to
act as an intermediary with Iran in discussions over the return of frozen
Iranian assets in the US. The Bank's action helped pave the way for the end
of the Teheran hostage crisis and generated goodwill in the US.
It will be some time before the effects of the Ashridge restructuring become
clear. But it would be unwise to assume it marks the end of change at the
Bank.
The Bank's role and structure would be affected if ever there were moves
within the UK to give it more formal independence.
Then there is the Maastricht Treaty and its goal of a single European
currency and central bank. At present European economic and monetary union
seems a distant prospect and UK involvement unlikely. But will that always
be the case?
In the meantime, however, Mr George and Mr Pennant-Rea have stamped their
ideals and aspirations very firmly on an ancient institution. They now have
to ensure that their controversial restructuring produces the hoped-for
results.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
