<PROFILE>_AN-EG1ANAFQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940727
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of The Bank of England (2): More alert and
questioning - John Gapper on the supervisory role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two important anniversaries for the Bank fall this summer, in addition to
the tercentenary.
One is the 20th anniversary of the formation of a banking supervision
department. The other is the third anniversary of the traumatic closure of
the Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI).
Banking supervision was born out of crisis - the secondary banking crisis of
1973-74 - and remains an activity prone to scandal and upset. But the three
years since the BCCI debacle have been especially testing for the 250
supervisors who oversee the operations of 488 domestic and foreign-owned
banks in the UK.
This is partly because they have been absorbing a series of reforms intended
to meet criticisms of the Bank of England's supervisory style, made by Sir
Thomas Bingham in his inquiry into BCCI. But they have also had to operate
amid a public debate over whether they should do the job at all.
Although the Bingham criticisms were not followed by any visible change in
the senior ranks of banking supervisors, there has been a sea change in the
past year. The appointment last August of Michael Foot to succeed Roger
Barnes as head of banking supervision is the most visible sign.
Mr Foot, a 47-year-old career Bank of England man who had not worked in
supervision before, emphasises the change that has occurred. He talks of a
'more alert and questioning style' among officials who have traditionally
been less adversarial in their relations with banks than in other countries.
'There was an awful lot of good in what we did before, but there was a
feeling that we were too willing to take on trust everything that was said,'
he says. He argues that Bingham's call for the Bank to be able to switch to
a more aggressive style when demanded has been 'tremendously helpful'.
The Bank has resisted changing to US-style supervision, under which auditing
teams constantly examine banks' books. 'We are still nothing like the armies
of OCC (Office of the Comptroller of the Currency) investigators who pretty
well live in some of the big US banks,' says Mr Foot.
But it has placed more emphasis on review teams, which can spend two or
three days reviewing systems and controls at an institution. About 120 such
visits are made each year, and staff have received fresh training in fraud
awareness to be able to pick up signs that something is amiss.
This effort has been reinforced by a special investigations unit,
established after the Bingham inquiry, composed of 11 accountants with
'forensic' skills in analysing accounts to detect signs of fraud. The unit,
headed by Mr Ian Watt, is not based within banking supervision, but supports
it.
Mr Watt argues that supervisors have been 'glad to have someone to turn to
if they suspect fraud'. Some 170 cases have been referred to the unit since
it was set up, about half of which have required some action. Mr Watt says
that it gets many tip-offs from suspicious bank employees.
Yet although the unit has referred a few cases to police, there have been no
prosecutions so far. Mr Watt argues that the unit's deterrent effect is
valuable in itself. But he admits it is 'important that people are brought
to account, and the public sees they are properly punished'.
Mr Watt says that senior managements of banks co-operate with the unit's
inquiries willingly because they usually suffer from the effects of fraud by
employees or customers. 'Most banks are very much with us in our work
because they are usually the victims of these things,' he says.
At the same time, the Bank faces growing complexity in its core task of
supervising honest institutions. This is because of technological
innovation, and the growing emphasis in banks on securities, treasury and
derivatives trading. These areas require greater sophistication among
supervisors.
The Bank has a traded markets team which examines models used by banks. Mr
Foot says the Bank 'clearly cannot compete on a financial basis' to recruit
specialists in derivatives who could earn more outside, but some are keen to
have a stint at the Bank on their employment record.
These developments in supervision are one of the reasons he advances for
retaining the function within the Bank. He says that the Bank's role at the
heart of London money markets and the gilts market gives its officials
practical experience of financial markets rather than relying on theory.
The Bank's critics have two arguments for stripping it of supervision. One
is that financial boundaries are blurring, and banks should be regulated by
the same supervisor as securities firms and others. The other is that the
Bank's monetary role can conflict with its supervisory one.
Mr Foot admits that the structure of self-regulation for other bodies under
the 1986 Financial Services Act is still new - and 'not as intellectually
attractive' as having a single unified regulator. But he argues that the
main task is to ensure that regulatory efforts are well co-ordinated.
He cites relations with the Building Societies Commission, which he says
cause no difficulties of 'things disappearing down the cracks between us'.
He argues that other links must be developed similarly. 'We need to ensure
that our relations with all regulators are on the same basis,' he says.
On the second argument - that a central bank might hold back from deflating
an over-heated economy if banks would be bankrupted by asset price deflation
 -Mr Foot says the institutional arrangements are irrelevant. Such pressures
would 'emerge somewhere' in a monetary crisis.
The Bank's supervisors are able to celebrate the various anniversaries that
fall this summer without a sense of doom.
Despite the difficulties of BCCI, they have adapted their style and methods
enough to satisfy most critics without transforming the institution
completely.
Mr Foot emphasises the Bank's determination not to switch to 'ghastly
over-regulation' because of pressures to prevent scandals and collapse. Its
role remains primarily to protect depositors. 'A level playing field does
not mean that we have to smooth out every bump on the surface,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
