<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Survey of Tunisia (1): First steps taken to a place in the
developed world - Tunisia, an oasis of calm and economic growth in spite of
the political troubles that have affected neighbouring Algeria, hopes to
retain its political stability under President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali's
leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Tunisian government appears confident that it is getting many things
right, not least its vocabulary.
To western ears, the language sounds reassuringly familiar. Words such as
democracy, pluralism, privatisation, deregulation, modernisation and
structural adjustment trip off the official tongue with a persistence which
highlights the European-oriented ambitions of a nation increasingly less
enthusiastic about being identified primarily as Arab and north African.
But family and neighbours are hard to ignore, and Tunisia can do little
about either. On one border looms the large, unstable bulk of Algeria; on
the other the perverse, mercurial Libya of Col Muammar Gaddafi. Few of the
words which Tunisia employs to identify itself can fairly be used with
reference to either of its neighbours. As a result, and much to its
irritation, Tunisia finds its external image blighted by geographical
association.
Domino theorists, fashionable in south-east Asia before the collapse of
communism, are seeking to stoke similar fears about the surge of Islamic
fundamentalism in the Middle East. The strong electoral showing of the
fundamentalist parties in Algeria, and the country's subsequent descent into
political anarchy after the government refused to accept the verdict of the
electorate, must inevitably have implications for its neighbours.
But, 15 years after the revolution in Iran, there is little evidence to
support the view that Islamic fundamentalism is an exportable commodity,
despite the best efforts of the government in Tehran. Rather, the phenomenon
is being increasingly recognised as a response to the failure of individual
governments to alleviate poverty and diminish huge disparities in the
distribution of wealth.
The lesson appears to have been well understood in Tunisia. President Zine
El Abidine Ben Ali, nearing seven years at the head of the Tunisian
government, likes to describe his approach to ensuring continued political
stability as 'multi-dimensional'.
On the one hand, he is adamant that no political party based on religion
will be permitted. Reports by international human rights organisations
indicate that activists pursuing such aims are sometimes dealt with in ways
that are scarcely compatible with the liberal image that Tunisia is seeking
to foster. Police checkpoints on major roads at night underline the message
that the government will not compromise on security.
On the other hand, there is now a very modest representation of
non-government parties in the national assembly following the March
elections, and an apparent acceptance at the most senior level that this
process will be extended as standards of education and economic development
improve. However, the pace of democratic change will, at best, be
exceedingly slow. President Ben Ali was himself re-elected with an
improbable 99.9 per cent of the vote, and one of the two candidates who
failed to secure sufficient nominations to run against him was later
imprisoned for three months following an interview he gave to a Spanish
newspaper.
The Tunisian government's sensitivity to opposition and criticism may be
understandable in the regional political context, but it sits less
comfortably alongside the ambitions of a country which over the past decade
has taken considerable strides in stabilising, restructuring and
liberalising its economy. Tunisia now bears favourable comparison with much
of Africa and the Middle East over the way it has managed the transition
from a rigid state-controlled economy to one that is more and more
export-oriented and in which the private sector plays a steadily increasing
role.
Ministers are concerned that Tunisia's achievements have been too little
appreciated internationally and that too few countries, especially in
western Europe, have yet identified it as a focus for investment and as a
regional service centre. Their sales pitch can be persuasive. Tunisia is
close to Europe, with some 75 per cent of its trade carried out with EU
members. Barriers to trade have been progressively lowered and current EU
negotiations have as their eventual target the conclusion of a free trade
agreement. The population of 8.74m provides a modest domestic market, but
Tunisia is also well placed to supply the larger African and eastern
Mediterranean region.
The implementation of the structural adjustment programme has since 1987 won
plaudits from both the IMF and the World Bank, and contributed significantly
to the resilience of the economy in overcoming the impact of drought and the
Gulf war. Despite those negative factors, real growth has averaged 5 per
cent a year since 1989, while the current account and budget deficits have
been reduced last year to 4 per cent and 2.4 per cent of GDP respectively.
Inflation is estimated to be running at a little over 3 per cent, and there
has been continued success in reducing the percentage of export earnings
needed to finance external debt.
Meanwhile, reforms to the financial sector have produced greater banking
flexibility, a simplified system for both direct and indirect taxation, a
more coherent investment code, and the first steps towards the creation of
diversified capital market. The challenge now for both the government and
Tunisia's entrepreneurs is how best to exploit the improved institutional
framework in order to give the country the export-led growth it needs to
reduce an unemployment level of at least 15 per cent of the workforce, and
satisfy new entrants to the labour market.
The regional political environment urges caution, but the intensity of
international competition for investment funds demands speed. Nowhere is
this better illustrated than in the debate over privatisation. Given
Tunisia's experience since independence, it is not surprising that there is
no ready-made majority in favour of divestment. In some quarters free
enterprise and capitalism are still too readily associated with colonialism.
Additionally, the trade unions, which enjoy a political legitimacy
unparalleled elsewhere in the Arab world, are wary of possible job losses,
as indeed is the government.
But without an official lead, the nation's biggest companies seem unlikely
to accept the degree of transparency and dilution of ownership inherent in a
stock exchange flotation. If the government is truly committed to creating a
dynamic equities market that will serve to channel capital resources into
more productive investment, it will sooner or later have to set a more
emphatic example and bite the political bullet.
However this, as with so many other issues, may be delayed until the
government is convinced that the risk element has been reduced to a minimum
and no threat is posed to what is broadly defined as 'national consensus'.
Part of that process also involves wider social aims such as better health
care and education, regional aid and the provision of a strengthened safety
net to catch the most deprived members of society, including the 500,000 who
have been identified as requiring official help. Labour laws are also in the
process of being reformed, so as to provide for clearer definitions on terms
of employment, dismissal and wage bargaining, in which the government will
continue to play a key arbitration role.
President Ben Ali, looking out from his office in Carthage over the
magnificent sweep of the Mediterranean below, gives every impression of
being satisfied with more than his immediate environment. He and his
ministers believe they are well on the way to putting into place the
structures which will enable Tunisia to claim, eventually, a place among
developed nations. Their confidence will be more reassuring should Tunisia's
neighbours ever come to think along similar lines.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
