<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Billiton sale news hits Shell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
News that Shell Transport was poised to conclude the sale of its Billiton
metals business provided a motive to mark down the share price when it was
announced late yesterday.
The announcement that Gencor of South Africa had agreed to buy the most of
Shell's Billiton upstream assets for Dollars 1.14bn after charges contained
no surprises.
However, the shares had driven up by almost 10 per cent since the start of
the month and one oil specialist pointed out that while they normally traded
at a significant yield premium to the market the rising share price had
pushed the yield towards par.
Also, the US oil majors began their reporting season this week and the
figures have tended to match the gloomy forecasts. Yesterday Chevron
reported disappointing figures.
Shell Transport shares ended the day 10 lower at 732p, although the day's
final turnover of 2.5m shares suggested that the bears were merely shadow
boxing.
