<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / MoD rapped for 72% extra cost of Trident base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The construction of Britain's Trident nuclear submarine base has cost Pounds
1.9bn, 72 per cent more in real terms than originally expected, says a
report published by the National Audit Office today.
The cost overrun on the 10-year programme of works at Faslane in Strathclyde
and nearby Coulport reflects changes in nuclear safety standards, and a
failure by the Ministry of Defence to define precise requirements in the
early stages, the public spending watchdog says.
The programme, one of the biggest construction exercises in Europe, was
largely completed last July - a year later than planned - while some
individual projects have been delayed for more than two years.
The NAO describes the Trident works as a 'considerable technical
achievement' which had to contend with changes in safety standards and
sometimes unco-ordinated instructions from the ministry.
One of the biggest overruns was in spending on consultancy, which ran to
Pounds 360m against an original projection of Pounds 78m. A giant shiplift,
as tall as an 11-storey building and as long as a football stadium, cost
nearly three times more than anticipated, at about Pounds 340m.
The watchdog found that in the MoD 'problems of co-ordination frequently
arose' because 'a large number of authorities had an interest in defining
the works requirement'. Only after 1991 was there a single point of
authority for project definition.
The project was managed for the defence ministry by the Property Services
Agency, the government's property management body, both before and after the
agency's privatisation in 1992.
The NAO says there were defects in the reporting arrangements between the
ministry and the agency, leading to a failure of control over design
changes. These problems were largely corrected after April 1992.
It was originally hoped that the base would be ready for sea trials of the
first Trident submarine in June 1992. This deadline was eventually
abandoned, but because of the initially strict timetable contracts were
entered without agreement on precise designs. As design changes became
necessary, and stricter safety standards were imposed, the contractors were
able to demand extra time and money.
</TEXT>
