<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Legal position of receivers changed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The legal position of receivers over their liabilities to staff was
yesterday brought into line with that of administrators following the
controversial Paramount Airways case.
A High Court judge ruled - in a decision involving receivers for Leyland Daf
and Ferranti - that receivers have the same personal liability to employees
as administrators and are equally liable for holiday and severance pay and
other benefits in staff contracts.
In the Paramount case earlier this year the Court of Appeal ruled that
administrators were personally liable to employees in these areas.
Its ruling prompted protests from the insolvency profession, which warned
that administrators would have to approach their jobs in a radically
different way to avoid these liabilities and that this would threaten
thousands of jobs.
The House of Lords is due to hear the Paramount case in December.
</TEXT>
