<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Pupil-teacher ratio rises again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The pupil-teacher ratio in English schools has risen for the fifth year in
succession, John Willman writes.
Provisional figures released yesterday by the Department for Education show
that there were 18.1 pupils for each teacher in nursery, primary and
secondary schools in January, up from 17.8 a year earlier. In primary
schools, the pupil-teacher ratio rose from 22.4 to 22.7. The ratio increased
from 16.2 to 16.4 in secondary schools (excluding sixth-form colleges).
During the past year the number of school children has increased by 2 per
cent. The full-time equivalent number of teachers in such schools has risen
by just 0.3 per cent.
