<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Financial advisers 'fail to meet need'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A stark mismatch between the type of financial advice consumers want and
what is provided by the financial services industry is set out today in a
report from the National Consumers Council.
A survey by MORI, which forms the basis of the report, found that almost
nine out of 10 consumers thought it was important that financial advice
should be independent, while more than half thought it was difficult to find
that sort of advice.
Only about one in five people thought the information provided about
financial services was clear and easy to understand, and more than half
thought such information was hard to understand.
Such a perceived lack of clarity could be behind the anomaly between those
saying independent advice is important and those who seek such advice.
While 88 per cent of those questioned thought it important, if not
essential, that advice was genuinely independent, more than 40 per cent
would go direct to an insurance company, rather than an independent
financial adviser, for information about general insurance or life
insurance.
Only when investing a big sum or choosing a personal pension were IFAs the
category of adviser most likely to be approached.
Both are aspects of financial services where more than a quarter of those
questioned did not feel very confident about making the right choice, in
contrast with other products, such as current accounts or motor insurance,
where consumers felt more confident about their decisions.
Lady Wilcox, who chairs the NCC, criticised the 'meaningless marketing
material' and 'high-pressure sales tactics' to which consumers could be
subjected, particularly as decisions made about life insurance or personal
pensions could have serious consequences later if choices were based on
misleading or incomplete information.
Lady Wilcox said it was vital for consumers to have access to full and
impartial information, and welcomed the establishment of the Personal
Investment Authority, the new watchdog to protect the private investor.
She added, however, that there should be an early review of how effective
the PIA was, and warned that consumer interests had to be strongly
represented.
The survey highlighted how consumers tended to approach banks and building
societies for different products, even though similar services might be
available from both.
Seventy seven per cent would be most likely to go to a bank for advice about
a bank current account, for example, while only 11 per cent would go to a
society. On mortgages, however, 42 per cent would go to a society, while
only 17 per cent would go to a bank.
Consumer Concerns 1994: A Consumer View of Personal Financial Services.
National Consumer Council, 20 Grosvenor Gardens, London SW1W 0DH. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
