<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Refinery blaze hits Texaco contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Texaco has told some of its bulk customers that it will be unable to meet
certain supply contracts because of the fire at its refinery at Milford
Haven in west Wales.
The company cited force majeure, or forces beyond its control.
The affected contracts are those for delivery in Pembrokeshire, the site of
the refinery. Texaco also said it would be unable to meet swap arrangements
where payment was due in Pembrokeshire.
Oil companies routinely swap refined products to avoid having to ship them
to distant locations. These swaps would enable Texaco to meet its
commitments in other parts of the country.
Texaco said last night that it could not reveal the amounts involved in the
affected contracts. But it stressed that deliveries to Texaco petrol
stations would not be affected.
Other companies have said that they do not expect the closure of the
refinery to have any noticeable effect on either supplies or petrol prices
because of a refining capacity surplus. But it was expected that Texaco
might lose some market share because of its inability to supply from
Pembrokeshire.
Officials from the Health and Safety Executive began their investigation of
the damaged refinery yesterday, after the last fires had been extinguished.
Texaco said it expected them to make a preliminary statement today.
The fire, thought to have been started by a lightning strike on Sunday,
raged for 36 hours. It forced the closure of the refinery, which accounts
for 10 per cent of the UK's refining capacity. There were no serious
injuries.
</TEXT>
<XX>
