<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Tecs criticised as skills shortage is forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Widespread criticism of work-related education and of emerging skills
shortages is contained in two surveys published today.
A number of businesses also criticised Training and Enterprise Councils,
which are responsible for improving skills, and Local Enterprise Companies,
their Scottish equivalents.
A survey of engineering companies with fewer than 500 employees, published
by the Engineering Council, shows a shortage of engineers at all levels -
managerial, professional, technical and craft.
Nearly half of respondents felt that staff had insufficient engineering
skills and nearly 60 per cent were experiencing problems in finding
appropriately skilled staff, particularly at the technical level. Moreover,
72 per cent said they expected to need more engineers in the future.
The council said: 'The unfilled demand for engineers by small and
medium-sized companies will be a problem for many years to come unless the
perceived mismatch between the skills required by small and medium-sized
companies and the education, training and experience available is addressed.
'Companies ideally would like to see more vocational education courses which
include engineering, business skills and practical experience.'
A second survey, the latest quarterly research by the UK 200 group of
practising chartered accountants, showed three out of four of their clients
forecast a skills shortage. They urged the government to establish further
forms of both vocational and skills training.
Some 40 per cent of respondents, said to be a representative sample of 1,000
businesses including manufacturers, engineering companies, retailers and
service businesses, said they did not believe Tecs and Lecs were effective.
The Skills Required of Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises. The Engineering
Council, 10 Maltravers Street, London WC2R 3ER. Free.
</TEXT>
