<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Washington tries to salvage crime bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The White House and a congressional committee are working feverishly to find
common ground on tough anti-crime legislation that has a high priority in
the Clinton administration.
The group of proposed laws, known as the crime bill, passed the Senate and
House in varying forms this spring. But disputes over racial implications of
the death penalty, and over an assault weapons ban, have kept the bill for
weeks in a House-Senate conference committee. It was to meet late yesterday
for what could be final negotiations.
If a bill acceptable to all of Congress is not released this week, no
enactment is likely this year.
President Bill Clinton met leaders of the powerful Congressional black
caucus yesterday morning to seek a compromise on a provision in the House
version of the bill that would let defendants use statistics to challenge
the death penalty - allowed in 37 states - as racially biased.
Senate Republicans have threatened a filibuster to kill any crime bill that
includes 'racial justice' provisions.
Also causing trouble for the bill is a ban on 19 brands of assault weapon.
The ban passed the House and Senate but is adamantly opposed by Mr Jack
Brooks, House chairman of the conference committee. Many gun control
advocates in Congress think the ban in the final version of the bill will
have the votes to pass and so they feel the committee should not try to
compromise with Mr Brooks.
</TEXT>
