<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Radicals try to shatter Mideast peace process: Israelis see
growing threat from Iran and extremist groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE and DAVID HOROVITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
It seems no coincidence that yesterday's bomb attack on the Israeli embassy
in London - and the blast early today in North Finchley - came soon after
Israel and Jordan signed an historic peace accord in Washington.
Despite the handshakes and near euphoria of Israeli and Jordanian leaders in
Washington, the Middle East remains explosive.
The peace process, far from subduing Islamic fundamentalism, has spurred
Moslem radicals on - for fear they will become marginalised.
They are aware this means striking not only at Israel but also at moderate
Arabs such as the leaders of Egypt, Jordan and the Palestine Liberation
Organisation.
As a result, the peace process remains fragile and largely dependent on the
political survival of such men as Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak, Jordan's
King Hussein and PLO chief Yassir Arafat.
Israeli officials believe the embassy bombing in London may be linked to
bomb attacks earlier this month in Buenos Aires and Panama. In the Argentine
city, a car bomb ripped apart a Jewish cultural centre and killed at least
96 people. In Panama, 21 people, mostly Jewish businessmen, died when their
small aircraft blew up on a local flight.
The Israelis claim the bombings were part of a well planned effort by Iran,
and the Islamic groups it supports, to avoid being isolated by an emerging
alliance in favour of Middle East peace.
Israel has long wanted to see a new alliance emerge in the Middle East to
oppose Iran and its export of fundamentalism. The Israelis have pursued
peace in the past two years partly because they fear that, by waiting, they
could face Islamic regimes less willing to compromise.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, yesterday warned against 'extreme
Islamic radical terrorist movements', with infrastructure throughout the
world, following the radical teaching of Ayatollah Khomeini, the late
Iranian religious leader. Mr Rabin described the threat as 'Khomeinism
without Khomeini'. Moderate Arab governments, Israel and western states were
all at risk, he claimed.
A detailed picture of how such extremist groups operate is lacking. But
Israeli security officials believe they draw on a considerable network of
contacts and cells abroad. They train at bases in Iran, Pakistan and the
south of Lebanon, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed Hizbollah (Party of
God), the Israelis claim. A Lebanese group called Ansar Allah, Followers of
God, claimed responsibility for the Argentinian blast.
Israeli officials also believe that, while many of the groups operate
independently, they are bound together by a religious philosophy that
opposes western decadence and seeks to establish Islamic republics
throughout the Moslem world.
The groups are opposed to the Middle East peace process and to moderate
secular Arab leaders. They want to see the state of Israel destroyed. They
draw support from students and professional groups, attracting young people
with the lure of martyrdom.
The Hamas Islamic Resistance Movement is one such group operating in the
Palestinian self-ruled areas and the Israeli-occupied West Bank.
Israeli officials accuse Syria of continuing to allow extremists to operate
from Damascus. They claim President Hafez al-Assad could do much more to
halt Hizbollah and other Islamic groups. Israel says Mr Assad is pursuing a
two-track policy - using violence to force concessions in peace talks.
Israeli officials said the spate of bombings coincided with a renewed wave
of anti-Israeli activity by Hizbollah gunmen in south Lebanon. On Monday,
Hizbollah mounted a series of attacks on Israeli positions inside Israel's
security zone in south Lebanon, killing an Israeli officer and seriously
injuring another.
'It's all part of one connection in the struggle against Israel, compounded
by the desire to stop the peace process,' said Reserve General Shlomo Gazit,
former army intelligence chief.
Ten Palestinian groups opposed to the Israeli-PLO peace process are based in
Damascus, including Mr Ahmed Jibril's faction, which has threatened to
assassinate Mr Arafat.
Several of the groups yesterday condemned the Israeli-Jordanian accord as a
crime, marking a 'black day of mourning'. While these groups are responsible
for some violent attacks, they are divided between secularists and Islamists
and their alliance is regarded as short-term.
As the Middle East peace efforts continue, a battle against extremism is
likely to intensify.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ILZ  Israel, Middle East.
    USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
