<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Economic Watch: Greek current account boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's current account deficit fell sharply in the first four months
mainly thanks to increased transfers from the European Union structural
funds. The January-April deficit totalled Dollars 91m (Pounds 60m), against
Dollars 654m for the same period last year, according to central bank
figures. However, the underlying trade deficit worsened as exports fell by
12 per cent to Dollars 1.56bn, maintaining last year's steady downward
trend, while imports rose by 2.3 per cent to Dollars 5.88bn. The 32 per cent
rise in EU transfers, totalling Dollars 2.4bn, was due to much-increased
funding for infrastructure improvements, which is due to continue over the
next four years. At the same time, income from shipping and remittances from
Greeks working abroad declined by 6.5 and 1.3 per cent respectively, while
earnings from tourism rose by just 2.3 per cent for the first four months
this year.
Consumer prices in the west German state of Hesse rose 0.1 per cent in the
month to mid-July for a year-on-year increase of 3 per cent, the state
statistics office said. Baden-Wurttemberg reported consumer prices flat in
July compared with June and up 3 per cent from a year earlier. The figures
for North Rhine-Westphalia were 0.1 per cent and 2.7 per cent.
Ukraine's industrial output fell 36 per cent in the first six months
compared to the same period last year, but the downward trend has slowed
since May, the statistics ministry said.
</TEXT>
