<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Growth in exports boosts manufacturing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further evidence that UK manufacturers are witnessing steady economic
recovery emerged yesterday after a business survey reported that improving
exports contributed to the fastest rise in manufacturing order books for
almost six years.
But a sharp rise in the number of businesses expecting to raise prices and
indications that capacity constraints may develop in some manufacturing
sectors gave a hint that this faster growth might fuel inflationary
pressures later this year.
With Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, due to hold his
monthly meeting tomorrow with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, these
findings may add to speculation that interest rates will be raised soon.
The Confederation of British Industry's quarterly industrial trends survey,
for the three months to July, showed that one in five manufacturers expects
to raise prices in the next four months, while only 8 per cent expect to
reduce them.
In the previous survey, conducted in April, slightly more manufacturers were
expecting to reduce prices than raise them.
Sir David Lees, chairman of the CBI's economic affairs committee, yesterday
admitted that this change was 'worrying'. But he called on the government to
hold interest rates steady until at least the autumn. He said: 'In our
judgment, the inflation pressures are not sufficiently serious to suggest
that monetary policy should be tightened immediately.'
The price rises, he pointed out, were occurring from a relatively low base
and the continued intense domestic competition meant that manufacturers had
generally not been able to make price rises stick in recent months, even
where they had been expecting increases.
The Treasury yesterday welcomed the figures as evidence that the recovery
was 'becoming broader and stronger'.
With the government hoping that the recovery will become more export-driven
later this year, after being largely fuelled by domestic consumer
consumption last year, a steady rise in the reported level of export
performance was 'encouraging', Treasury officials said.
Meanwhile, concerns about the expectation of higher prices were yesterday
fuelled in the City by hints in the CBI survey that bottlenecks were
developing in some manufacturing sectors. The survey said the number of
companies working below capacity fell back to 54 per cent in the last
quarter, compared to 59 per cent in April.
The survey gave little sign that UK companies were yet seriously addressing
potential capacity constraints. Investment intentions grew at a relatively
weak rate last quarter, with only slightly more companies expecting to
increase their investment on plant and equipment than expecting to reduce
it.
The findings yesterday led Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the stockbroker, to
predict an earlier and larger increase in base rates, not least because the
expectation of higher inflation had been cited by Mr George as a factor that
would call for tighter monetary policy.
Details, Page 6
Lex, Page 18
London stocks, Page 38
</TEXT>
<XX>
