<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 94 / Railtrack and RMT agree to restart talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack and the RMT transport union last night agreed to resume talks over
the signalling dispute. The move came during the first 48-hour strike of
signalling staff, which is due to continue until noon tomorrow.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, responded positively to an appeal
made earlier yesterday by Mr Bob Horton, chairman of Railtrack, which owns
and maintains Britain's rail network.
The two sides are expected to meet at the offices of the conciliation
service Acas in the next few days. Their last such meeting ended in deadlock
on July 12.
Mr Horton told Mr Knapp in a letter that he was willing 'to negotiate
further on the offer on the table'. He added: 'We remain available at any
time to continue the process of negotiation on that basis.'
'We believe we have common ground,' said a Railtrack spokesman. 'All
elements of our last offer are negotiable.'
Last night Mr Knapp told Mr Horton: 'You are now apparently saying that you
are willing to negotiate further on all aspects of the offer on the table.'
He added: 'If you are saying - and I think you are - that you are ready and
willing to return to the negotiating table without constraints and
preconditions we are more than willing to resume talks.'
Mr Knapp said he found Mr Horton's letter 'a welcome confirmation of your
public stance' on being ready to negotiate.
Earlier yesterday Mr Knapp said that 'if Mr Horton is now saying there are
no 'no-go areas' and he is willing to negotiate freely then I am willing to
test Railtrack's sincerity in the next two days'. Mr Knapp added: 'If they
are genuinely seeking negotiations without excluding the issue of basic
rates, we are ready to meet at any time.'
Railtrack confirmed that it was willing to discuss basic pay rates.
Mr Knapp also said that the union was ready to negotiate a restructuring
package for the signalling grades through a joint working party.
Yesterday Railtrack said up to 30 per cent of train services ran in the
afternoon, despite the start of the RMT's first 48-hour stoppage, while 34
per cent of the network was open. But the company warned it might be hard to
maintain that level of service with the problems of getting trains into
position.
The opening of signal boxes at Colchester in Essex and Three Bridges in
Sussex meant that services from London Liverpool Street to Norwich and from
London Victoria to Gatwick airport were possible for the first time during
strike action.
Red Star, the parcels service owned by British Rail but currently up for
sale, said it was diverting packages from rail to road and air.
Trying to bridge a gap, Page 7
</TEXT>
