<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / International Company News: American Express hit by weakness
at Lehman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After-tax profits at American Express fell 14 per cent in the second three
months of the year. It blamed lower profits at Lehman Brothers, the
investment bank which was spun off during the period.
Had it not been for Lehman, the US financial services company's earnings
would have advanced 19 per cent, to Dollars 359m, on the back of higher
spending on its charge cards and similar products.
Lehman, which last week revealed that its second-quarter results had
suffered from poor trading conditions in financial markets, was accounted
for as a discontinued item.
American Express reported net income of Dollars 357m, or 69 cents a share,
on revenues of Dollars 3.5bn, compared with Dollars 416m, or 83 cents, on
revenues of Dollars 3.3bn a year before.
The growth in earnings from continuing operations was driven by a 12 per
cent rise in spending billed to the company's cards, to Dollars 34.6bn. The
total number of cards was 5 per cent higher than a year before.
Despite this, card fees fell slightly, to Dollars 431m, reflecting
competition between issuers. On the other hand, revenues from fees charged
to merchants, which have been under pressure in recent periods, rose 9 per
cent to Dollars 983m.
American Express also reported continued profit growth at its IDS Financial
Services subsidiary, up 21 per cent to Dollars 109m. The subsidiary's name
is to be changed to American Express Financial Advisers at the beginning of
next year, the company said. The move reflect's chairman Mr Harvey Golub's
desire to retain only those businesses which add to the overall brand image
of the group.
For the first six months, net income was up to Dollars 710m from Dollars
659m the year before.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>American Express Co.
    IDS Financial Services.
    American Express Financial Advisers.
</CO>
