<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: Switch benefits Wellcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pharmaceutical group Wellcome rose 10 to 644p as it responded to firm US
buying with investors said to be switching out of UK sector leader Glaxo.
The move was seen as a response to the positive underlying tone of the most
recent interim trading report from Wellcome and the legal problems which
bedevil Glaxo.
Wellcome last week reported sales of its best-selling drug, the anti-herpes
treatment Zovirax, ahead 15 per cent in the 10 months to the end of June.
However, there had been confusion over the figures as the company had
changed its accounting period to a calendar year end and the shares had been
initially marked down.
Subsequent press comment suggested that, if Wellcome failed to exploit the
over-the-counter market for Zovirax, other cash-rich groups might see it as
a plausible takeover target. Glaxo faces the threat of generic competition
to its Zantac ulcer drug. The shares fell 6 to 568p in the wake of Friday's
legal claims and counter claims over the plan by Novopharm of Canada to sell
generic Zantac pills based on Form 1 of the medicine.
