<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow edges up in lacklustre
trading session
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices edged higher yesterday in a lacklustre session highlighted
by the second-quarter results of the leading US energy groups, writes Frank
McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 6.80 better at 3,741.84, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was up 1.14 at 454.25. Volume on
the Big Board was a light 211m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was up 0.61 at 434.06,
and the Nasdaq composite added 0.20 to 716.88.
The restrained tone which had dominated trading last week carried over to
yesterday's opening. Prices opened firmer but failed to make much headway,
with the market held in check by renewed uncertainty over the timing of the
Federal Reserve's next move to tighter money.
With Mr Alan Greenspan's recent warning on interest rates still ringing in
the ears of equity investors, the market looked for inspiration elsewhere
and came up empty. Activity in the bond market was as non-committal as in
stocks, and there was but a shred of second-tier economic guidance on offer.
The National Association of Realtors announced that sales of existing homes
last month had dropped 3.6 per cent. The news, while was nominally
supportive of a scenario which sees the Fed delaying its next strike on
rates, was merely shrugged off.
Instead, Wall Street concentrated on further news on how the corporate
sector fared during the second quarter. The overall impression was not
particularly favourable, but few stocks were hit hard.
Wall Street was, however, disappointed with the big oil groups, which
reported their downstream profit margins had come under pressure as crude
prices climbed during the second quarter. Among the companies publishing
their results, Mobil closed down Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 84 3/8 and Texaco
was unchanged at Dollars 63. But Exxon added Dollars 1/2 to Dollars 58 1/4 ,
even though its results fell short of expectations.
By contrast, Black &amp; Decker surprised analysts by posting
better-than-expected earnings of 24 cents, up from 20 cents in the
year-earlier period. The tool maker's stock was marked up Dollars 1 1/4 to
Dollars 18 3/4 .
Capital Cities/ABC appreciated Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 79 3/4 on its
announcement of net income of Dollars 1.23 a share, up from 92 cents a year
ago. CBS dipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 309 as the media group commenced a
programme to purchase 3.5m shares at Dollars 325.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed slightly lower in light trading with the the TSE-300
composite index slipping 7.77 points, or 0.19 per cent, to 4,168.39.
Declines led advances 399 to 315. Volume of 41.60m shares was below Friday's
56.13m shares and trading value was CDollars 465.0m compared with CDollars
470.4m.
American Barrick announced a bid, which it valued at CDollars 14 a share,
for all of Lac Minerals' outstanding shares. Barrick's shares lost CDollars
1 to CDollars 31 3/8 . Royal Oak Mines, which launched a bid for Lac earlier
this month, was up CDollars 1/4 to CDollars 5 7/8.
</TEXT>
