<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / International Company News: Coal &amp; Allied feels effects of
lower prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Coal &amp; Allied Industries, which is majority-owned by CRA, the Australian
mining group, yesterday reported an 86 per cent fall in after-tax profits to
ADollars 5.9m (Dollars 4.4m) in the six months to end-June. This compared
with ADollars 40.7m in the same period a year previously.
Operating profit after tax, but before abnormals, stood at ADollars 14.3m,
compared with ADollars 37.3m, while abnormals amounted to a ADollars 8.4m
loss, resulting from the restructuring of the open-cut mines. In the
previous year, there was an abnormal gain of ADollars 3.4m.
The company said total production in the six-month period was 5.1m tonnes,
down from 5.7m tonnes a year earlier, although part of the reduction was due
to the sale of certain operations. Reduced coal contract prices and the
stronger Australian dollar meant that sales for the half-year fell from
ADollars 334.5m to ADollars 283.4m.
Coal &amp; Allied said the still-lower coal prices negotiated with leading
Japanese buyers earlier this year and the stronger currency would mean that
profits remained under pressure in the short-term. However, 'increased
demand coupled with low stockpiles is expected to increase prices in the
next 12 months', it said.
The dividend was cut to 25 cents a share from 44 cents.
</TEXT>
