<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / International Company News: Poor results for three big US
energy groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Three big US energy groups produced disappointing second-quarter results
yesterday, reflecting lower profit margins from refined products due to the
rebound in oil prices in recent weeks.
The higher oil price repaired some of the damage done late in 1993 and early
this year to exploration and production profits at Exxon, Mobil and Texaco.
However, this was more than countered by the higher costs faced by
downstream, or refining and marketing, operations, which were unable to
raise prices sufficiently to offset the rebound in the price of the
commodity.
Two of the three, Mobil and Texaco, were also held back by restructuring
costs announced this month.
Exxon, which reported its lowest quarterly after-tax profits since the last
quarter of 1989, saw exploration and production earnings fall by a 11 per
cent, to Dollars 603m.
The company blamed the drop on the fact that oil prices were on average
Dollars 2 a barrel lower than the second quarter of 1993, despite the recent
run-up.
Before one-off charges, Mobil's upstream earnings slipped 15 per cent and
Texaco's fell 37 per cent, to Dollars 335m and Dollars 155m respectively.
Downstream earnings, meanwhile, showed a reverse of the first three months
of the year.
At that time, profit margins had swollen as the companies benefited from
lower input costs. In the second quarter, Exxon's refining and marketing
profits slid 50 per cent, to Dollars 201m; Texaco's fell 41 per cent, to
Dollars 106m; and Mobil's slipped 8 per cent, to Dollars 224m (all figures
before one-off items).
Echoing comments from the other companies, Mr Alfred DeCrane, Texaco
chairman and chief executive, blamed the poor downstream results on rising
costs. 'Market conditions precluded recovery of these added costs to the
refining and marketing units,' he said.
One bright spot for the US oil majors has been the rebound in profitability
at their chemicals businesses in recent quarters. In the latest period,
Exxon said profits had jumped to Dollars 110m, from Dollars 50m a year
before.
Both sales and profit margins in the chemicals business improved during the
latest quarter, and profits have now risen in four consecutive periods, said
Mr Lee Raymond, Exxon's chairman.
Mobil recorded earnings of Dollars 39m from chemicals, almost as much as the
Dollars 44m it made in the whole of last year. Texaco reached agreement
recently to sell its chemicals operations, and accounted for these
operations as a discontinued business.
