<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Two more companies use FIDs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROD ORAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Marling Industries and Adam &amp; Harvey announced foreign income dividends
yesterday, doubling the number of companies that have taken advantage of
rules in last year's budgets to relieve surplus advance corporation tax.
The FID scheme was designed to help companies which derive a substantial
portion of their profits abroad. They pay abnormally high taxes when their
UK corporation tax liabilities are insufficient to offset the ACT they have
paid on their conventional dividends.
The first two companies to announce FIDs were BAT Industries, the tobacco
and financial services group which earns about 70 per cent of its profits
abroad, and Courts, the household furniture retailer which has a large
Singapore subsidiary.
A number of other companies are suffering from surplus ACT, particularly
after their UK profits shrank during the recession. However, companies are
proving slower to adopt FIDs than tax advisers had expected.
Several companies such as Burmah Castrol, the lubricants maker, and Keller
Group, a recently floated construction company, have expressed interest in
FIDs but have yet to implement them. The tax changes allowing companies to
pay dividends from foreign income without incurring ACT came into effect on
July 1.
Marling Industries, an industrial textiles maker, said yesterday that its
FID would save Pounds 200,000 in ACT, which it would pass on to its
shareholders via an increased dividend.
A final pay-out of a net 0.57p is recommended, making a total of 0.77p
(0.65p), on a capital base increased 10 per cent by a rights issue last
July. The increased dividend will compensate non-tax paying institutional
shareholders which would have clawed back the ACT on conventional dividends.
Adam &amp; Harvey, an international distributor and steel stockholder, is
recommending a final dividend of 11p gross payable as a FID, making a total
of 18.5p gross for the year. This represents a 23 per cent increase for
non-tax paying shareholders and 42 per cent for UK tax payers.
The board said it would review annually the balance between ordinary and
foreign income dividends, and it is probable the current balance would alter
as unrelieved, carried forward ACT, now standing at about Pounds 400,000, is
absorbed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
